Task 1: Installing and Configuring Wireshark
Subtask 1.1: Install Wireshark
First, we need to install Wireshark and its dependencies on our Linux system.

# Update package repositories
sudo apt update

# Install Wireshark
sudo apt install wireshark -y

# Install additional network tools for traffic generation
sudo apt install curl wget dnsutils -y
Subtask 1.2: Configure User Permissions
To capture packets without running Wireshark as root, we need to configure proper permissions.

# Add current user to wireshark group
sudo usermod -a -G wireshark $USER

# Set capabilities for dumpcap (packet capture utility)
sudo setcap cap_net_raw,cap_net_admin=eip /usr/bin/dumpcap

# Verify the configuration
getcap /usr/bin/dumpcap
Note: You may need to log out and log back in for group changes to take effect.

Subtask 1.3: Launch Wireshark
Start Wireshark from the command line:

# Launch Wireshark GUI
wireshark &
If you're using a headless system, you can use tshark (command-line version):

# Check available network interfaces
tshark -D
Task 2: Capturing Network Traffic
Subtask 2.1: Identify Network Interface
Before capturing traffic, identify the active network interface.

Using Wireshark GUI:

Open Wireshark
Look at the interface list on the main screen
Identify the interface with activity (usually eth0 or ens33)
Using Command Line:

# List all network interfaces
ip addr show

# Show interface statistics
ip -s link show
Subtask 2.2: Start Packet Capture
Method 1: Using Wireshark GUI

Double-click on the active network interface (e.g., eth0)
Wireshark will start capturing packets immediately
You'll see packets appearing in real-time
Method 2: Using tshark Command Line

# Start capturing on eth0 interface (replace with your interface)
sudo tshark -i eth0 -w capture.pcap

# Capture with packet count limit
sudo tshark -i eth0 -c 100 -w capture.pcap
Subtask 2.3: Generate Network Traffic
Open a new terminal window and generate various types of network traffic:

# Generate HTTP traffic
curl -I http://httpbin.org/get
curl -I http://example.com

# Generate DNS queries
nslookup google.com
dig facebook.com
host github.com

# Generate HTTPS traffic
curl -I https://www.google.com
wget -q --spider https://www.github.com

# Generate continuous ping traffic
ping -c 10 8.8.8.8
Subtask 2.4: Stop Capture
In Wireshark GUI: Click the red square Stop button in the toolbar

In tshark: Press Ctrl+C to stop the capture

Task 3: Filtering and Analyzing Packets
Subtask 3.1: Basic Wireshark Interface Navigation
Familiarize yourself with the Wireshark interface:

Packet List Pane (top): Shows summary of each packet
Packet Details Pane (middle): Shows detailed protocol information
Packet Bytes Pane (bottom): Shows raw packet data in hexadecimal
Subtask 3.2: Apply HTTP Filters
Filter captured traffic to show only HTTP packets:

Display Filter for HTTP:

http
More specific HTTP filters:

# HTTP GET requests only
http.request.method == "GET"

# HTTP responses only
http.response

# HTTP traffic to specific host
http.host == "example.com"

# HTTP status codes
http.response.code == 200
Steps to apply filters:

Type the filter in the Display Filter bar at the top
Press Enter or click the Apply button
Only matching packets will be displayed
Subtask 3.3: Apply TCP Filters
Analyze TCP traffic patterns:

Basic TCP filters:

# All TCP traffic
tcp

# TCP traffic on specific port
tcp.port == 80

# TCP SYN packets (connection establishment)
tcp.flags.syn == 1

# TCP connections to specific IP
ip.addr == 8.8.8.8 and tcp
Advanced TCP analysis:

# TCP retransmissions (potential network issues)
tcp.analysis.retransmission

# TCP out-of-order packets
tcp.analysis.out_of_order

# TCP window size issues
tcp.analysis.window_update
Subtask 3.4: Apply DNS Filters
Examine DNS queries and responses:

DNS filters:

# All DNS traffic
dns

# DNS queries only
dns.flags.response == 0

# DNS responses only
dns.flags.response == 1

# DNS queries for specific domain
dns.qry.name contains "google"

# DNS error responses
dns.flags.rcode != 0
Subtask 3.5: Combine Multiple Filters
Create complex filters using logical operators:

# HTTP or HTTPS traffic
http or tls

# DNS and HTTP traffic
dns or http

# Traffic to/from specific IP excluding SSH
ip.addr == 192.168.1.1 and not ssh

# Web traffic (HTTP and HTTPS)
tcp.port == 80 or tcp.port == 443
Task 4: Identifying Network Anomalies
Subtask 4.1: Analyze Traffic Patterns
Look for unusual patterns that might indicate security issues:

High-frequency connections:

# Filter for connections to unusual ports
tcp.port > 1024 and tcp.port < 5000

# Look for repeated connections
tcp.flags.syn == 1
Suspicious DNS activity:

# DNS queries to unusual domains
dns and not (dns.qry.name contains "google" or dns.qry.name contains "facebook")

# DNS queries with long domain names (potential DGA)
dns.qry.name matches ".*\..*\..*\..*\."
Subtask 4.2: Identify Potential Security Issues
Look for these indicators:

Port Scanning Activity:

Multiple TCP SYN packets to different ports
TCP RST responses indicating closed ports
Unusual Protocol Usage:

HTTP traffic on non-standard ports
Unencrypted protocols carrying sensitive data
DNS Anomalies:

Queries to suspicious domains
High volume of DNS requests
Subtask 4.3: Analyze Packet Details
For suspicious packets:

Right-click on a packet of interest
Select Follow → TCP Stream or HTTP Stream
Examine the complete conversation
Look for:
Unusual user agents
Suspicious file transfers
Encoded or encrypted payloads
Task 5: Exporting Data and Analysis
Subtask 5.1: Export Filtered Data
Save specific packet data for further analysis:

Export specific packets:

Apply your desired filter
Go to File → Export Specified Packets
Choose format (PCAP, CSV, etc.)
Save the file
Command line export with tshark:

# Export HTTP traffic to new file
tshark -r capture.pcap -Y "http" -w http_traffic.pcap

# Export to CSV format
tshark -r capture.pcap -Y "http" -T csv > http_traffic.csv

# Export specific fields
tshark -r capture.pcap -Y "dns" -T fields -e dns.qry.name -e dns.resp.addr
Subtask 5.2: Generate Traffic Statistics
Create statistical reports:

Using Wireshark GUI:

Go to Statistics → Protocol Hierarchy
View Statistics → Conversations
Check Statistics → Endpoints
Using tshark command line:

# Protocol statistics
tshark -r capture.pcap -q -z io,phs

# Conversation statistics
tshark -r capture.pcap -q -z conv,tcp

# DNS statistics
tshark -r capture.pcap -q -z dns,tree

# HTTP statistics
tshark -r capture.pcap -q -z http,tree
Subtask 5.3: Create Analysis Report
Document your findings:

# Create analysis script
cat > analyze_capture.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash

PCAP_FILE="capture.pcap"
REPORT_FILE="network_analysis_report.txt"

echo "Network Traffic Analysis Report" > $REPORT_FILE
echo "Generated on: $(date)" >> $REPORT_FILE
echo "=================================" >> $REPORT_FILE

echo "" >> $REPORT_FILE
echo "1. TOTAL PACKETS CAPTURED:" >> $REPORT_FILE
tshark -r $PCAP_FILE -q -z io,stat,0 | grep "Packets" >> $REPORT_FILE

echo "" >> $REPORT_FILE
echo "2. PROTOCOL DISTRIBUTION:" >> $REPORT_FILE
tshark -r $PCAP_FILE -q -z io,phs >> $REPORT_FILE

echo "" >> $REPORT_FILE
echo "3. TOP CONVERSATIONS:" >> $REPORT_FILE
tshark -r $PCAP_FILE -q -z conv,tcp | head -20 >> $REPORT_FILE

echo "" >> $REPORT_FILE
echo "4. DNS QUERIES:" >> $REPORT_FILE
tshark -r $PCAP_FILE -Y "dns.flags.response == 0" -T fields -e dns.qry.name | sort | uniq -c | sort -nr | head -10 >> $REPORT_FILE

echo "" >> $REPORT_FILE
echo "5. HTTP HOSTS:" >> $REPORT_FILE
tshark -r $PCAP_FILE -Y "http" -T fields -e http.host | sort | uniq -c | sort -nr >> $REPORT_FILE

echo "Analysis complete. Report saved to $REPORT_FILE"
EOF

# Make script executable
chmod +x analyze_capture.sh

# Run the analysis
./analyze_capture.sh
Task 6: Advanced Analysis Techniques
Subtask 6.1: Time-based Analysis
Analyze traffic patterns over time:

# Traffic volume over time (1-minute intervals)
tshark -r capture.pcap -q -z io,stat,60

# Packets per second
tshark -r capture.pcap -q -z io,stat,1
Subtask 6.2: Geolocation Analysis
For external IP addresses, you can perform basic geolocation:

# Extract unique external IP addresses
tshark -r capture.pcap -T fields -e ip.src -e ip.dst | tr '\t' '\n' | grep -E '^[0-9]+\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+$' | grep -v '^192\.168\.' | grep -v '^10\.' | grep -v '^172\.' | sort | uniq > external_ips.txt

# Display the list
echo "External IP addresses found:"
cat external_ips.txt
